{"session_id":"2e64652f-e6b7-4740-87f9-531f84ad18cb","transcript_path":"/Users/jinayoon/.claude/projects/-Users-jinayoon-HogTTV/2e64652f-e6b7-4740-87f9-531f84ad18cb.jsonl","cwd":"/Users/jinayoon/HogTTV","permission_mode":"acceptEdits","effort":{"level":"high"},"hook_event_name":"Stop","stop_hook_active":false,"last_assistant_message":"---\n\n**Why it was done**\n\nThis commit completes the user-facing half of the extension. The preceding commit (`b9e547c`) established the backend plumbing — manifest, permissions, and the service worker that fetches and caches Slack emoji data. This commit wires that data into the actual Google Meet experience: without it, the cached emoji list would sit unused with no way for the user to access it.\n\n**What changed**\n\nFour files were added across two concerns. The content script (`content.js` + `content.css`) is injected into every `meet.google.com` page: it watches for the chat input to appear via `MutationObserver`, injects a 🏷 button next to it, and on click shows a floating 320px picker overlay with a search box and an 8-column emoji grid. Selecting an emoji inserts `:emoji_name:` as text into the chat input. A second MutationObserver + `TreeWalker` pass also scans incoming chat messages and replaces any `:name:` shortcodes with inline `<img>` tags, so received emojis render visually for the current user. The popup (`popup.html` + `popup.js`) provides the settings surface: token entry, a \"Sync emojis\" button that delegates to the background worker, cache age display, and a clear/reset action.\n\n**How it fits**\n\nThis is the final piece of the two-commit scaffold. `b9e547c` owns the Slack API layer; this commit owns everything the user actually sees and touches. The separation keeps cross-origin fetch out of the content script entirely — the content script only reads from `chrome.storage`.\n\n**Agent context**\n\nThe goal was a picker-button-only experience (no autocomplete, no auto-render on send — just a clickable button). The TreeWalker-based rendering of incoming shortcodes was added on top because \"view\" was part of the original feature request. Multiple chat input selectors are tried in order because Google Meet's DOM changes frequently and no single selector is reliable long-term. Intent captured at `2026-05-14 03:06:05` by `claude-sonnet-4-6`."}

