{"session_id":"dd8ca49f-4f54-41c2-8f77-bb9d468d20d8","transcript_path":"/Users/jinayoon/.claude/projects/-Users-jinayoon-HogTTV/dd8ca49f-4f54-41c2-8f77-bb9d468d20d8.jsonl","cwd":"/Users/jinayoon/HogTTV","permission_mode":"acceptEdits","effort":{"level":"high"},"hook_event_name":"Stop","stop_hook_active":false,"last_assistant_message":"Now I have everything I need. Here's a tight 2-minute demo script:\n\n---\n\n## Hoggit Demo Script — 2 minutes\n\n### Framing (what to say, what to show)\n\n**[0:00–0:18] — The problem**\n\n*Say:* \"Git was built for humans. When you run `git blame` today, you see who changed a line and when. But you don't see *why*.\"\n\n*Show:* Terminal. `git blame src/rate_limiter.py -L 42,42` → a SHA, a date, a name. Then `git show <sha>` → a diff and a useless commit message: `\"Fix rate limiter\"`.\n\n---\n\n**[0:18–0:45] — Three rails**\n\n*Say:* \"Now agents write most of the code — in huge commits, fast. The prompt, the plan, the tradeoffs they considered: all of that gets thrown away. Three months later, someone on support is staring at a broken rate limiter and has no idea why it works this way.\"\n\n*Show:* `hoggit show <sha>` — same commit, but now the terminal renders three sections below the diff:\n- The commit message (unchanged)\n- The original prompt: `\"Rate limiting fires for everyone after the LB change. Investigate.\"`  \n- The plan/decisions: the XFF header reasoning, the constraints, what they ruled out\n\n*Say:* \"Hoggit stores that context as git-native blobs hanging off the commit. It travels with `git push`, it survives rebases. You can read it like any other ref.\"\n\n---\n\n**[0:45–1:15] — /hoggit-explain**\n\n*Say:* \"But the raw intent is still a wall of text. So we wired it into Claude Code.\"\n\n*Show:* In Claude Code, type `/hoggit-explain <sha>`. Claude reads the diff + commit message + intent and outputs a 4-section synthesis:\n\n> **What changed:** The IP extraction helper in the rate limiter now reads `X-Forwarded-For` instead of the socket peer address.  \n> **Why it was done:** The new NLB preserves client IP at L4, but Contour terminates TLS — so every request looked like it came from Envoy's pod IP.  \n> **Agent context:** Captured 2026-05-13 by claude-opus-4-7. Constraint: only honor XFF when the request came through trusted ingress. Alternative considered: RFC 7239 `Forwarded` header — skipped because Envoy emits XFF.\n\n*Say:* \"Not just what changed. Why — and what they decided not to do.\"\n\n---\n\n**[1:15–1:35] — Automatic capture**\n\n*Say:* \"You don't have to do anything extra. Hoggit hooks into Claude Code's event system. Every time an agent makes a commit, the intent — the prompt, the plan it built, the conversation — gets captured and attached automatically.\"\n\n*Show:* Quick flash of `.hoggit/hooks.log` tailing — `PostToolUse: git commit` → intent bound. Or a split-second of `hoggit intent` showing a pending intent getting promoted to a commit SHA.\n\n---\n\n**[1:35–2:00] — Overlap detection + close**\n\n*Say:* \"And because agents can work in parallel now, there's one more thing: if two developers — or two agents — are editing the same files, the server notices before either of them commits.\"\n\n*Show:* A macOS system notification slides in: `\"Heads up: alice is also editing src/rate_limiter.py\"`. Then the same message appears inline in Claude Code's context for the next turn.\n\n*Say:* \"Hoggit. Version control for agentic coding — because the why matters as much as the what.\"\n\n*Show:* Terminal. `hoggit --help`. Fade.\n\n---\n\n### Production notes\n\n- **Repo to use in the recording:** Use the `hackathon-agentgit` repo itself — it has real hoggit intents on its commits, so `hoggit show` and `/hoggit-explain` will produce real output, not mocked data.\n- **Sequence to record first:** The overlap notification is the hardest to stage — set it up with two terminal sessions before recording so the notification fires on cue.\n- **Pacing:** The `/hoggit-