{"session_id":"e50dcf12-88bc-4372-b7bd-f9a15cd35e8b","transcript_path":"/Users/jinayoon/.claude/projects/-Users-jinayoon-HogTTV/e50dcf12-88bc-4372-b7bd-f9a15cd35e8b.jsonl","cwd":"/Users/jinayoon/HogTTV","permission_mode":"acceptEdits","effort":{"level":"high"},"hook_event_name":"Stop","stop_hook_active":false,"last_assistant_message":"The fix is committed. Here's what was happening and what changed:\n\n**Root cause:** `PROCESSED_ATTR` (`data-slack-emoji-rendered`) was set on the parent element after rendering an emoji. When Google Meet receives a new message, it sometimes refreshes the DOM for earlier messages — restoring their text content to the raw shortcode (`:bufo-alarma:`) while the `PROCESSED_ATTR` attribute stays on the element. The TreeWalker's `closest()` check then saw the attribute and skipped that node, so `:bufo-alarma:` stayed as plain text while `:bufo-excited:` (in a fresh element with no attribute) got rendered.\n\n**Fix:** Removed the `PROCESSED_ATTR` tracking entirely. The guard was never needed for infinite-loop prevention — once a text node is replaced with `<img>` elements, there's no shortcode text left for the walker to match. And when Meet does restore text content, re-rendering is exactly what we want."}

